HB 4137
1 (b) The entry of a plea under paragraph (a)(B) of this subsection constitutes a waiver of trial
2 and consent to the entry of a judgment forfeiting the presumptive fine.
3 (c) A no contest plea under this subsection is not subject to the requirements of ORS chapter
4 135 relating to the entry of pleas and, upon receipt of the plea, the court may enter judgment
5 against the defendant without taking further evidence.
6 (4) The court may require that a defendant requesting a trial under subsection (3) of this section
7 deposit an amount equal to the presumptive fine established under ORS 153.019 and 153.020 or such
8 other amount as the court determines appropriate if the defendant has failed to appear in any court
9 on one or more other charges in the past. If the defendant does not deposit the amount specified
10 by the court, the defendant must personally appear in court at the time indicated in the summons.
11 The amount deposited by the defendant may be applied against any fine imposed by the court, and
12 any amount not so applied shall be refunded to the defendant at the conclusion of the proceedings.
13 (5) The court may require a defendant to appear personally in any case, or may require that all
14 defendants appear in specified categories of cases.
15 (6) If a defendant has entered a no contest plea in the manner provided in subsection (3) of this
16 section, and the court determines that the presumptive fine is not adequate by reason of previous
17 convictions of the defendant, the nature of the offense charged or other circumstances, the court
18 may require that a trial be held unless an additional fine amount is paid by the defendant before a
19 specified date. Notice of an additional fine amount under this subsection may be given to the de-
20 fendant by mail. In no event may the court require a total fine amount in excess of the maximum
21 fine established for the violation by statute.
22 (7) If a defendant fails to make a first appearance on a citation for a traffic violation, as defined
23 by ORS 801.557, fails to make a first appearance on a citation for a violation of ORS 471.430, or fails
24 to appear at any other subsequent time set for trial or other appearance, the driving privileges of
25 the defendant are subject to suspension under ORS 809.220.
26 (8)(a) A defendant who has been issued a violation citation for a traffic violation and who
27 has already transferred the defendant’s interest in the motor vehicle described in the cita-
28 tion is not required to make a first appearance and may instead notify the court, in the
29 manner provided by the Judicial Department, of the transfer when:
30 (A) The citation is issued for the parking, abandoning or operation of the motor vehicle;
31 (B) The defendant transferred interest in the vehicle to another person before the cita-
32 tion was issued;
33 (C) The defendant submitted the notice of transfer of interest to the Department of
34 Transportation as required under ORS 803.112; and
35 (D) Pursuant to ORS 803.117 the defendant is exempt from liability.
36 (b) Upon receiving verification from the Department of Transportation that the person
37 is exempt from liability in accordance with ORS 803.117, the court shall dismiss the citation.
38 The citation may be reissued to the transferee if the name is shown on the notice of transfer
39 form submitted by the defendant under ORS 803.112 and only if the jurisdiction verifies that
40 the transferee appears to have been the owner at the time of the violation.
41 SECTION 2. The amendments to ORS 153.061 by section 1 of this 2026 Act apply to con-
42 duct occurring on or after the effective date of this 2026 Act.
